The title of this post refers to a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/04/science/turtles-vanish-in-black-hole-soup-pots-and-pans-of-china.html">NY Times article</a> from 1999 and not much has changed especially in South East Asia.

Illegal trade and habitat loss continue to threaten our turtles with the majority of the world's most endangered turtles coming from the region. In the last few months, several reports on turtle trade

&nbsp;

A recent TRAFFIC report, <a href="http://www.traffic.org/species-reports/traffic_species_reptiles38.pdf"><em>Seizures of Tortoises and Freshwater Turtles in Thailand 2008-2013</em></a>, analyzes 53 reported seizures of tortoises and freshwater turtles in Thailand. Even though seizures were significant,  insufficient follow-up takes place. Also a loophole in Thailand's primary legislation facilitates the illegal wildlife trade:
"Although trade in these species is prohibited or restricted under various national and international legislations in Thailand, current legislation allows for the seizure of non-native species only at the point of entry or exit, and not within the country. It is therefore not illegal to hold or trade non-native CITES-listed species within Thai borders."

The majority of turtles seized in the last 4 years in Thailand are Indian Star Tortoises, which are banned for commercial trade and illegal

&nbsp;

An estimated 1.5 to 2 million eggs are collected each year, although the authors believe current figures may be considerably higher and are continuing to rise, according to their report <a href="http://www.traffic.org/species-reports/traffic_species_reptiles39.pdf"><em>Assessing The Trade In Pig-Nosed Turtles </em>Carettochelys insculpta <em> in Papua, Indonesia</em></a> (PDF, 2 MB), released on World Animal Day.

