"The idea of citizen participation is a little like eating spinach: no one is against it in principle because it is good for you.

[...] There is a critical difference between going through the empty ritual of participation and having the real power needed to affect the outcome of the process."

- "A Ladder of Citizen Participation" [Arnstein 1969]

&nbsp;

Although the article was written to address "what citizen participation is and what is its relationship to the social imperatives of our time", some of the ideas and criticisms of different levels of citizen participation seem relevant to new citizen science and crowdsourcing projects that are becoming fashionable for research institutes and governments.

<a href="https://biodiversityconnections.wordpress.com/?attachment_id=1420" rel=" rel=&quot;attachment wp-att-1420&quot;"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1420 aligncenter" src="https://biodiversityconnections.files.wordpress.com/2015/12/8-rungs-on-ladder-of-citizen-participation.png?w=265" alt="8 Rungs on Ladder of Citizen Participation" width="265" height="300" /></a>

